  2023,"04",/general-conference/2023/04/41christofferson,Elder D. Todd Christofferson,64,"Interestingly, B. H. Roberts ran for Congress again in 1898, this time with First Presidency consent, and was elected. Given the deep prejudice against the Church at that time, however, and the fact that he had engaged in plural marriage, the House of Representatives refused to seat him. Nevertheless, in hearings before the House regarding his service, B. H. was an eloquent and impassioned defender of the Church and its doctrine. (SeeSaints, 3:83–86; Truman G. Madsen,Defender of the Faith: The B. H. Roberts Story[1980], 241–72.)"
  2023,"04",/general-conference/2023/04/41christofferson,Elder D. Todd Christofferson,65,"See1 Corinthians 12:14–27."
